The theme reflects on human nature so well, and coupled with the superb acting, takes me into this classy, elegant and well polished world. text: This movie was friggin spectacular.  A mutating gem that is dark, comedic, bloody, hilarious, bleak, symbolic, poetic, morally thought provoking, enlightening, elegant, insane, romantic, and personal all at once.   Okja was a bit obvious in its tonal shifts. But with Parasite, I think Bong Joon finally hit the motherload of tonal balance. The film is unclassifiable because its everything blended seamlessly into each other. Easily one of the best of the year.   Just awesome in every way.  *Edit:* Thank you for all the likes! Please go vegan for your health, the environment, and for the ethical treatment of animals!

text: The tonal shift in this film is so gradual that you barely even realize it's happening. In the beginning it feels like a comedy, but over time your anxiety builds to the point of wanting to hit the stop button, or at least pause to brace yourself for what's to come next. But like any other film, to get the most out of the experience you have to endure it. This for me was difficult as I haven't felt this uncomfortable during a film since Fargo. But it was well worth the effort. This may have not been the most productive year for cinema, but damn. Did we get to view some bangers. Endgame and this were enough to say 2019 was one of the best years in the history cinema.

text: Wow. I just watched this movie and it broke my heart. I lived like that wealthy family in Korea and we always were surrounded by other wealthy families. I never imagined or even saw people who were in poverty like the ones portrayed in the movie. I remember my parents friends saying how poor people smelled bad and just thought that was normal. We treated our maids and chauffeurs like second class citizens and forgot about their humanity and their equality. I lived with big hopes and dreams and so carelessly because I never had to worry about food, my clothes, or anything else for that matter. We lived like kings and treated our fellow man who did not have as much as trash that can be discarded anytime. Just seeing that there was a whole another side to Korea filled with poverty stricken people trying to survive put me in a state of shock as I watched the movie. How foolish I have been to think that everyone in Korea lived as we did. My heart goes out to the people struggling everywhere in the world and I have to say this movie humbled me. I hope one day I could be a man who can help these people get on their feet and find new hope in life instead of living just to survive.

text: For anyone searching to answer this question: "Is Parasite a horror film?" YES. Most of it falls under "thriller" but expect to feel uncomfortable for most of it until that morphs into outright displeasure as horrible events ensue in this wild ride down the river of insanity. A thought-provoking film for sure because of the questions it raises about economic disparity, although your time would be better served in that regard by reading economic reports. I believe the WHO site has a wealth of resources. Anyway, "at your own risk" folks. Cinematography is undeniably stellar though - I will give credit where it is due.

text: here 5 films recommended for you guys who are interested in korean movies. The five films have got loved by so many korean people.   1. 국제시장 (Gukje Market) - a story of a man who had been going through the rapid social, economical, cultural changes from the middle of 20c of korea. When you watch this movie, you will get how the most of elders in korea have been living their each life with so many hardship. https://youtu.be/BBEDtovULHY https://youtu.be/L3Chxh1hg_Q  2. 태극기 휘날리며 (Taegukgi : Brotherhood of War) -After I have wached this movie, I felt that this movie is similar to Saving Private Ryon. But the background is about the Korean war (1950~1953). https://youtu.be/gTXxTxI-m-c  3. 변호인 (the Attorney) - the attorney, who is the main character of this movie is based to president No Moo Hyun in korea who had governed from 2003 to 2007. President No Moo Hyun have fought against to dictatorship when he was a lawyer, then after the dictatorship got replaced to democratic age, He has become one of the mostly loved politician. https://youtu.be/QDaG0IF7ucc  4. 서편제 (Seopyonje) - "Seo" means westside, "Pyonje" means a clique or style of sings (or singers) among Pansori, which is the representative traditional song of korea. When you watch this movie, You may feel the spirit of art in old age korea. https://youtu.be/sdjwD4jW4XY  5. 암살 (Assassination) - in modern days, korea was a colony of japan. Then there were so many people who protested against to violence of japan. This movie is also treating the armed resistance episode of the "Independence Army" to kill japanese military general and the pro-japanesed korean politicians. https://youtu.be/jLs5zf5XtGo

text: So, my girlfriend comes out of the movie yesterday saying she has a multitude of feelings and needs to "let them settle" before she can comment on it. The word I was searching for came forth in "hubris", which ultimately made this an entertaining movie . As you may recall in the story of "Daedalus", Icurus's fatal flaw is hubris. He is too arrogant with the wings his father made for him. Despite being warned, he flew too high and the wax melted, causing Icarus to fall to his death. This family in Korea had a fatal flaw of hubris, as seen in their drunken revelry at the master's home while the family was away. They had it made with what they had accomplished, but they could not maintain their integrity due to excessive pride and overconfidence. The threshold of hubris guilt was when they entertained the thought of marrying into the family. The end result of hubris is nemesis, and is seen when the father flees, becomes self-isolated, "vanishes into thin air", and family be damned. Worthy of a Greek tragedy. The other compelling comment is the larger issue with Pres Trump's denouncement of the movie. Is that not hubris on a grander scale? Peace and out. Dabo.

text: All of these comments convinced me to watch the movie. If you’re here wondering what genre it is, all I will say is that it’s almost comedic in the beginning and progresses into a thriller by the end. Please trust me and don’t look for any spoiler videos if you’re planning on watching it. You have to go through the roller coaster of emotions without any spoilers during this film. After you’ve watched the movie, look up an explanation video. The video doesn’t really matter much, unless you were confused, it’s the comments that made me gasp in realization at some of the things that people were bringing to my attention. There are so many callbacks in this film that I would recommend watching a things you missed video and also reading the comments on those. If you’re still not sure about whether or not you should watch this movie, I am telling you right now that I was in the same place and definitely do not regret it. There were some parts of the movie that gave me chills just from how the lines were delivered or the intense music (or the shocking lack of it). Please go watch the movie

text: But one of the most important metaphor has been overlooked!!! " *Icing* *on* *cake* " When Mr Kim is trying to convince Mrs Park that the old maid has TB... *Jessica* is the one who suggests “If you get the chance the hot sauce(pizza sauce)  will be icing on the cake" Mr kim uses it  and Mrs park is confirmed about the tb thing  Then later Mrs park narrates the story about the ghost in which she tells that her son kept thinking about the cake because he loved (particularly) the icing on that cake - the reason he discovered the ghost  In the end we see that Jessica is asked to carry the cake that has the same icing as before and when the ghost guy stabs she slams the cake on his bloody face leaving half his face stained  with blood and half with icing " That is the reason the pizza scene is so important The proverb icing on the cake means an attractive but unimportant addition ... The icing probably represents the temptations that led to their downfall..

text: The story is so well balanced between the two families, that you can't even tell who the lead actors or the supporting ones are. It is also one of those very few movies which don't have a clichéd Hero-Villain storyline. The way it dealt with social discrimination and flaws in human nature is beyond extraordinary. It clearly explains why it is only the third film in history to win both the Palme d'Or and Academy Award for Best Picture. A rare masterpiece indeed. Don't get why some people still have the guts to call it "overrated" or term it as an "average movie".

text: I liked the film, but I didn't like the name. What does "Parasite" have to do ...?! The only parasites there are the husband of the first housekeeper and the second after, for obvious reasons. One family was rich, the other poor. The poor started to work for the rich in exchange for money, only with unethical methods. The rich woman was 'madame', but in her own way she took care of the children and the husband who loved her. I even thought that "parasite" referred to the money ... Well, if it was " Trickery" or "Lack of Ethics" or "Clumsy Climbers" or "Between Rich and Poor" or  "Discrepancies", would not draw much attention. Thankfully Bong Joon-ho explained the name of the film...
